@@yThe Great Oasis and the Deepwell Confluence@@N

@@eBefore the Keepers of Measure surveyed their first road, the Great Oasis already
existed as a confluence of three underground springs rising through fractured
limestone into a shallow basin. The earliest name, preserved on pre-dynastic clay
seals, is the Deepwell Confluence. The oasis did not sit on the road; the road
existed because the oasis did.@@N

@@WThe Keepers built the world's first hydraulic regulation system here: the Cistern
Ring, a series of underground catchment chambers arranged in a ring below the
basin. Four chambers governed by four sluice masters formed the Water Court, the
earliest known governing body in the eastern desert. Their decisions were carved
into the Waystone Circle, twelve upright limestone slabs surrounding the oasis,
each bearing the Charter of Passage.@@N

@@yThe Measuring House stood at the center, observatory and archive in one. Its
walls were aligned to true cardinal within a thumb-width. Narrow roof apertures
let sunlight fall on calibration marks at specific times. From this building,
the gnomon stone provided the master shadow reference against which all road
alignments and survey calculations were calibrated.@@N

@@dThe High Water Court became the supreme arbitration body for water-right disputes
across the entire road network. When the Ninth Meridian Rite failed and the Iseth
Reach dried, the basin shrank to less than half its area. The Water Court
fractured into Pragmatists, Legalists, and Ritualists. The Battle of the Dry
Basin destroyed the Toll Pavilion and killed the last High Water Judge.@@N

@@eThe oasis endures as the corridor's heart. Spring Wardens still ration by
consensus, maintaining the closest approximation of the original charter system.
Every inscription is both a claim to water and a claim to history. The corridor's
fate has always been decided here, where all desert roads meet water.@@N
